    <h1>CHI&#xAD;NESE VI&#xAD;O&#xAD;LET PRO&#xAD;DUCES ED&#xAD;I&#xAD;BLE LEAVES</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This herb (right) was a gift. Can you help iden­tify it?</p>
    <p>Ade­line G.L. Thio</p>
    <p>The shrub is botan­i­cally known as Asys­ta­sia ganget­ica. Its com­mon names in­clude Chi­nese Vi­o­let and Ganges Primrose.</p>
    <p>It is of­ten grown as an or­na­men­tal ground­cover plant in lo­cal land­scapes and, at times, it es­capes cul­ti­va­tion and be­comes a weed.</p>
    <p>The leaves are ed­i­ble as a leafy veg­etable and are stripped from the fi­brous stems be­fore cook­ing.</p>
    <p>stlife@sph.com.sg</p>
    <p>Answers by Dr Wil­son Wong, an NParks-cer­ti­fied prac­tis­ing hor­ti­cul­tur­ist, parks man­ager and ISA-cer­ti­fied ar­borist. He is the founder of Green Cul­ture Sin­ga­pore and an ad­junct as­sis­tant pro­fes­sor (Food Sci­ence & Tech­nol­ogy) at the Na­tional Univer­sity of Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>Have a gar­den­ing query?</p>
    <p>E-mail it with clear, high-res­o­lu­tion pic­tures of at least 1MB, if any, and your full name to stlife@sph.com.sg. We re­serve the right to edit and re­ject ques­tions.</p>

